e in the practical exercise of combined arms. In Monty and the Canadian Army, John A. English analyses the way Montgomery’s operational influence continued to permeate the Canadian Army. For years, the Canadian Army remained a highly professional force largely because it was commanded by "Monty men," found at almost every lower level of army command, who were steeped in the Montgomery method. The era of the Canadian Army headed by such men ceased with the integration and unification of Canada’s armed forces in 1964. The embrace of Montgomery by Canadian soldiers stands in marked contrast to negative perceptions by Americans, only a few of whom have viewed him in a favourable light. Monty and the Canadian Army aims to correct such perceptions, which are mostly superficial and more often than not wrong, and addresses the anomaly of how this gifted general, one of the greatest field commanders of World War Two, managed to win over other North American troops.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGeneralszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zCanada. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh  aBattle of the Rhineland.  aBattle of the Scheldt.  aCanadian Army.  aEuropean operations.  aGeneral B.L. Montgomery.  aGeneral G.G. Simonds.  aMonty’s men.  aNormandy Campaign.  aPost-war Canadian Army.  aWWII.  aWorld War Two.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753536040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487535360423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487535360/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles